{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527640"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:31:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:31:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14212"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14212"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.01,0.06,0.05,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96068"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6898"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78800"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12740"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37305"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96068"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. Her regular medications include metformin and perindopril. She mentions that she often struggles to afford her medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her HbA1c is 8.2% (66 mmol/mol).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step to improve this patient\u0027s access to medications?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Register the patient for the Closing the Gap scheme","Provide free medication samples","Switch to once-daily dosing regimens","Prescribe generic medications only","Refer to a hospital outpatient clinic"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step to improve this patient\u0027s access to medications is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eregister the patient for the Closing the Gap scheme\u003C/strong\u003E. This scheme is a key initiative aimed at reducing health disparities between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Australians by improving access to healthcare services and medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Closing the Gap scheme provides eligible Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people with access to PBS medicines at a lower cost or for free. By registering this patient for the scheme, she would be able to access her necessary medications at a reduced cost, addressing her concern about affordability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing generic medications only\u003C/strong\u003E may help reduce costs to some extent, but it does not address the systemic barriers to healthcare access that the Closing the Gap scheme aims to overcome. While generic medications are generally cheaper, they may still be unaffordable for some patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring to a hospital outpatient clinic\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary in this case and would not directly address the issue of medication affordability. The patient\u0027s conditions (diabetes and hypertension) can typically be managed effectively in primary care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to once-daily dosing regimens\u003C/strong\u003E might simplify the medication schedule but would not necessarily make the medications more affordable. This approach does not address the core issue of cost.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding free medication samples\u003C/strong\u003E is a short-term solution that does not address the ongoing need for affordable medication access. It is also not a sustainable practice and may raise ethical concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy registering for the Closing the Gap scheme, the patient can receive ongoing support for medication access, which is crucial for managing her chronic conditions effectively. This approach aligns with the broader goals of improving health outcomes and reducing disparities for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Closing the Gap scheme aims to reduce disparities in health outcomes between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Australians.","The scheme provides access to subsidised medications for eligible Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people.","Patients must be registered for the Closing the Gap scheme to access its benefits."],"references":["Trivedi AN, Kelaher M. Copayment Incentive Increased Medication Use And Reduced Spending Among Indigenous Australians After 2010: A study of government-sponsored subsidies to reduce prescription drug copayments among indigenous Australians. Health Affairs. 2020 Feb 1;39(2):289-96."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78800"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14212"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78800"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-30T21:41:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T14:18:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6898"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96068"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}